In Prin. 74 it occurs, as here, in a conditional sentence:

Aut si demutant mores ingenium tuom, Neque eos antiquos seruas, ast captas nouos, Omnibus amicis morbum tu incuties grauem.

The word is naturally rare in Plautus, since it belongs to a diction removed from colloquial language; but there seems no reason for refusing it a place in his plays. In this passage its ‘raison d'etre⁷ is the appropriation of at to another use ‘at least’ (v. 684). In the Augu-stan poets it came into fashion again. They use it as a substitute for at, where the metre requires a long syllable. In the second cent. A.D. it passed into prose.
